        <figcaption id="img-caption">A photo taken in 1953 at her home by Alfred Eisenstaedt.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <div id="tribute-info">
        <h2>A history of Marilyn Monroe:</h2>
      </div>
      <div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>1926</strong> - Born June 1st, in Los Angeles as Norma Jeane</li>
          <li><strong>1944</strong> - Discovered by photographer David Conover</li>
          <li><strong>1946</strong> - Signed her first studio contract with 20th Century Fox and changed her name to Marilyn Monroe</li>
          <li><strong>1947</strong> - Contract is dropped</li>
          <li><strong>1948</strong> - Signs with Columbia Pictures and will lend a decent singing voice to a musical, Ladies of the Chorus</li>
          <li><strong>1952</strong> - Gets her first Life magazine cover</li>
          <li><strong>1953</strong> - Niagara premieres and is her breakthrough performance. Marilyn’s beguiling Lorelei Lee, the now-classic performance of “Diamonds Are a Girl’s Best Friend,” and perfect comedic timing establish her as a star.</li>
          <li><strong>1954</strong> - Marriage to baseball star Joe DiMaggio but later that year divorce and films the famous skirt-blowing scene from The Seven Year Itch before hundreds of spectators in midtown Manhattan</li>
          <li><strong>1955</strong> - Starts up her own Production company named Marilyn Monroe Productions. Enrolls in the Actors Studio, run by Lee Strasberg and comes out with Seven Year Itch</li>
          <li><strong>1956</strong> - Converts to Judaism and marries the playwright Arthur Miller</li>
          <li><strong>1959</strong> - Goes on to win the Golden Globe Award for Best Actress</li>
          <li><strong>1961</strong> - Marilyn and Arthur Miller are divorce and she checks into a New York psychiatric clinic later on</li>
          <li><strong>1962</strong> - Wins World Film Favorite at the Golden Globe Awards. In May, Marilyn sewn into a see-through sequined dress, performs a breathy rendition of “Happy Birthday” for President John F. Kennedy. On August 5th, she was found dead in her Brentwood home, of an apparent barbiturate overdose.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div id="quote">
        <p>"Imperfection is beauty, madness is genius and it's better to be absolutely ridiculous than absolutely boring."</p>
        <p>-- Marilyn Monroe</p>
      </div>
      <div id="more-info">
        <p>Read More about this unforgettable women at <a href="https://www.americanheritage.com/marilyn-monroe-chronology#7" id="tribute-link" target="_blank">American Heritage.</a></p>
      </div>
    </main>
